AB  - Explores the late-19th-century pluralistic, multiethnic Catholic parish, Immaculate Heart of Mary Catholic Church (IHM) in Currie, MN, in terms of accounting for its longevity, ie, its success & unity despite parishioner ethnic & linguistic difference. The origins & development of IHM is traced from its founding by Bishop John Ireland & John Sweetman. Interethnic cooperation in church matters as a direct offshoot of extensive interaction outside the church is cited as the key reason for IHM's success as a multiethnic parish. This community interaction is described, & the role of Oliver & Ann Drinville as "cultural brokers" between Currie's disparate religious, socioeconomic, & ethnic groups is explained. Attention is then given to the character of cooperation in the church. D. Edelman
